<p><em><strong>October 14th, 2023:</strong></em> Greetings from Taipei. I hosted a meetup this week with  who has a great newsletter on embracing ‚Äú<a href="https://citygirlslowlife.substack.com/?utm_source=mention&amp;utm_content=writes" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Slow Life</a>‚Äù in Hong Kong after moving to 20 countries in a couple of years with a remote company. Thanks to all friends new and old who came out. I‚Äôm planning on hosting one in Barcelona the week of November 12th when we are there for the month so let me know if you will be around.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7d15a302-d72f-4027-a2da-cf8cbebee213_1211x909.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ztRkzJjQ55RgQJsXp8MqsjJvB_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/un99Gt0d-yDyNnEsg7OOEJ4r6hpb4ernXw4Bzk1-10o=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3ZDE1YTMwMi1kNzJmLTQwMjctYTJkYS1jZjhjYmViZWUyMTNfMTIxMXg5MDkuanBlZw== 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wi- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WDztzkfj2BAuj0KxiSx68sk2t- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XlAZERKA_Pwm3ZCLW3dkI7MPwZAnvnq_23qZoN6KumI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2QxNWEzMDItZDcyZi00MDI3LWEyZGEtY2Y4Y2JlYmVlMjEzXzEyMTF4OTA5LmpwZWc=" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/VCFHYEmAG4pO9N5S1H9NDq2J0bMFh0lc2GH9-M9Zlb4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3ZDE1YTMwMi1kNzJmLTQwMjctYTJkYS1jZjhjYmViZWUyMTNfMTIxMXg5MDkuanBlZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/U8nbqyJueEoYNPQwS6M5OhpYxlTAUVu_4mpALaCPjzk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2QxNWEzMDItZDcyZi00MDI3LWEyZGEtY2Y4Y2JlYmVlMjEzXzEyMTF4OTA5LmpwZWc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XlAZERKA_Pwm3ZCLW3dkI7MPwZAnvnq_23qZoN6KumI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2QxNWEzMDItZDcyZi00MDI3LWEyZGEtY2Y4Y2JlYmVlMjEzXzEyMTF4OTA5LmpwZWc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p><a href="https://boundless.substack.com/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><h2>#1 A Clarity Session In Bali</h2><p>Over the last 6.5 years, I‚Äôve been extremely independent. I do almost everything myself, even the mental strategizing about how to think about everything I‚Äôm doing. On one level this is a bit crazy but on another, it‚Äôs given me incredible freedom over my time. Without other people to work with, I can actively drop the ball on almost anything at any time. And I have, embracing time abundance to wander, contemplate, take time off, spend time with Angie and now my daughter, and start up new creative projects on a whim.</p><p>But with a cute baby in the mix, someone who I have a hard time ignoring when she‚Äôs in the same room, a lot of the things that I just sort of took care of in the open spaces of time are not getting done anymore. This means when I do sit down and work for a 3-4 hour stretch, which I‚Äôm doing about 1-2 times a week in Taiwan, I‚Äôve been just catching up on admin stuff, not the creative work that fuels me.</p><p>While I do plan to work a little more when we leave Taiwan, this whole admin-first default is unsustainable and a risk to my desire to keep going. The whole point of this path is not to maximize any sort of traditional metric of success but to maximize aliveness and time flexibility.  While I am lucky to have many things I enjoy doing, my previous approach of focusing mostly on creative work and then doing the maintenance work that is necessary as it comes up is just not cutting it anymore.  </p><p>Luckily I had a thought partner to think through a new approach while I was in Bali last week. A friend of the newsletter , who is <a href="https://georgtanner.substack.com/p/the-purpose-crisis" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">living with his wife and two kids in Bali</a>, offered to do a ‚Äúclarity session‚Äù with me around everything I was working on. His general understanding of my work shared life priority of designing work around his family, and his ability to synthesize ideas in real-time made him a wonderful thought partner.</p><p>He used a tool, Miro, which I haven‚Äôt really explored but was perfect for something like this as it helped turn my words into a clear visual map. For example, laying out all the things I was working on, it became obvious that I was trying to do A LOT of stuff:</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F82bfb2c3-75d3-46c0-adb3-ff7e86daba73_1246x616.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/cqcA02IsACjtCwOOpyMLZ0r_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/E7JF8ty_L40qHGFTI9Syu1LtPJgqXJf_MjBU26_Bl-Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY4MmJmYjJjMy03NWQzLTQ2YzAtYWRiMy1mZjdlODZkYWJhNzNfMTI0Nng2MTYucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/VOyVqlqyZN9xC7kuePKsNmQVxW- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Ft5Nw0RZSVUK9L5bbM0JYjH8g0MZYQZWZ7Lxs-d6CQ8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGODJiZmIyYzMtNzVkMy00NmMwLWFkYjMtZmY3ZTg2ZGFiYTczXzEyNDZ4NjE2LnBuZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/zjC_" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/V48dFSXnD-jHx2pDs6OKXFDR_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/W83Ga-9hQk_NFv9Yhjp4u7awLE9wC_ss_20QFfHm9Nc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY4MmJmYjJjMy03NWQzLTQ2YzAtYWRiMy1mZjdlODZkYWJhNzNfMTI0Nng2MTYucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>all my stuff mapped out</figcaption></figure><p>I did this in text form <a href="https://boundless.substack.com/p/i-listed-out-everything-im-working" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">a few weeks back</a> and it was helpful in terms of seeing how much was going on but something about visually doing it made it seem easier to work with. Looking at everything, I sort of laughed and was able to say, ‚ÄúOkay well it wouldn‚Äôt be reasonable to crush all of this, especially since I‚Äôm actively choosing to spend more time with family right now.‚Äù When I graded myself, I realized that only the writing here and my podcast were the things I was consistently able to do at a high level. This is because they are easy for me. I love writing this newsletter and no matter how little time I have, it gets done.  But for the other stuff, if I want them to happen, I‚Äôm going to need another approach.</p><p>The other thought I had looking at this map was, WOW. I feel so lucky that almost all of these things are emergent from my own experiments over the last 6+ years. I literally get to work on things that I like, entirely of my own creation, and that combined support our family financially. This is fantastic.</p><p>Another thing you‚Äôll notice is that there are two clear sides. The stuff on the left is where I love spending my time. This newsletter, my podcast, my community, and my book. Prior to publishing The Pathless Path, I spent about 80% of my time and made about 2% of my money on these activities. After publishing the book, it‚Äôs still been close to 70% of my time but now almost 40-50% of my income.  I‚Äôm still adjusting to this shift and while I‚Äôve treated the increased attention to my work as permission from the universe to double down on it, I‚Äôd be lying if I said I wasn‚Äôt still a little uncomfortable betting it all on this path. I don‚Äôt trust it‚Äôs going to be financially viable yet. While others see me as at the start of some big mission, to me it still feels very uncertain and my rational mind still wants to hedge so that we can keep living the life we want for now.</p><p>With a baby in the mix, my total time has shrunk dramatically especially being in Taiwan where I‚Äôve been supporting Angie in taking advantage of all the things like fitness and art that are so much more familiar for her in her home country. What this means is that when I sit down to do focused work, I‚Äôve been spending most of my time doing maintenance for StrategyU and other projects and then being a bit frustrated that I don‚Äôt have time to create.</p><p>I did a thought exercise of what I‚Äôd do if I was handed $10 Million. I quickly said:</p><ul><li><p>I‚Äôd gift StrategyU to someone to run or sell it at a discount to a consultant trying to quit their job</p></li><li><p>I‚Äôd keep doing this newsletter, shift more attention to writing books, and the community, and would hire a researcher and business manager to help me with all of it</p></li><li><p>I‚Äôd spend a lot more on rent and also moving services so that we could go between places a little more smoothly</p></li></ul><p>While this kind of thinking makes it clear what I see as important and helps me think of ways to do some of this now, there are still many tradeoffs I need to make.  From the session with Georg, I realized that a lot of what has been holding me back from shifting into a new mode has been conflicting feelings with how I think about my path. </p><p><em><strong>I have a powerful sense of abundance, faith, and trust</strong></em> that things will work out. I have no intention of quitting anything anytime soon. It‚Äôs okay to deprioritize some of the creative projects I want to be working on in the short term.</p><p><em><strong>I trust</strong></em> that if I keep going with my writing here in this newsletter, share my book, and continue having deep conversations on the podcast, good things will happen. Never bet against curiosity and the internet.</p><p><em><strong>I am also afraid</strong></em> that book sales will slow, interest in my StrategyU training and courses will slow with the economy, our cost of living will rise in the US, and I may not have the time to dedicate to creating new offers.</p><p><em><strong>But I have faith</strong></em> and evidence that I can easily react to a change in circumstances and reinvent myself and new kinds of work like I have done 50 times before.</p><p><em><strong>I am afraid</strong></em> that if I bring people on to support me I will have to spend time ‚Äúmanaging‚Äù people, moving away from creative work. But I‚Äôve also realized by actually searching for people to help me, that what I see as ‚Äúadmin,‚Äù others actually love doing.</p><p>This is the reality of an unconventional path. There are tons of positives but uncertainty is always there for the ride. For me, it‚Äôs a feature, as I get to have a clear view of what I‚Äôm really feeling and have no choice but to face it and move forward.</p><p>Here‚Äôs the plan I developed with Georg over the coming months:</p><p><em><strong>The core mission:</strong></em> Focus and attention on what I love doing: writing, having conversations, and acting as a node to connect others on unconventional paths. Focus on building and investing around the newsletter, podcast, and book.</p><p><em><strong>The tactical next steps</strong></em> in the next three months:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Develop a clearer brand and mission around my work:</strong> </p><ol><li><p>Read <em>Category Pirates</em> suggested by Charlie Hoehn and go through reflection exercises - what ‚Äúproblem‚Äù does Pathless Path solve?</p></li><li><p>Figure out the next steps for the Boundless newsletter. To stay on substack or move somewhere with more customization for readers?</p></li><li><p>Get more marketing support help for the podcast and YouTube to continue promoting the book</p></li></ol></li><li><p><strong>Strengthen and revamp the Find The Others community</strong></p><ol><li><p>Bring on a contractor to help improve communication around the offer and develop a sustainable plan for the next 2-3 years (in progress)</p></li><li><p>Focus less on attending live events in the community &amp; more focus on creating tools &amp; materials that help people on unconventional paths</p></li></ol></li><li><p><strong>Reduce the time I spend on StrategyU to only content &amp; teaching/coaching</strong></p><ol><li><p>Define more clearly what I don‚Äôt want to do</p></li><li><p>Find a contractor (in progress) to help with marketing, content &amp; operations</p></li><li><p>Explore partnerships, investigate selling the business, and other strategic options</p></li></ol></li></ol><p>I think one thing I realized in the session was that I needed to take a step back to take a step forward. It‚Äôs okay to focus on maintenance mode for the next few months instead of only half-committing to everything. I‚Äôve started working with two contractors and I‚Äôm already realizing that tedious work for me can be enjoyable work for others. Despite setting an intention to spend more on the ‚Äúbusiness‚Äù this year, I‚Äôve struggled to find the right people who are a ‚Äúhell yeah.‚Äù But two people I just started working with have me feeling a lot better. and I‚Äôm excited to ‚Äúspend‚Äù to do more creative work, which is really the only thing that matters for my path over the long term. </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F53960bd7-1fdb-4808-b593-701d62554437_1469x820.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/nKqcYOQJy8N4hw_b6Nm6T2_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7nxdlmVwtW2BGIF- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ED- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/4izTE7J37aNUsBinF8Kq1iDy2m-" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/6- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7N2SZXUp8A- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jUDg9D-qjmzm214xhTl0hjWBsjptKDkijJlC_1GQ_bs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNTM5NjBiZDctMWZkYi00ODA4LWI1OTMtNzAxZDYyNTU0NDM3XzE0Njl4ODIwLnBuZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>Onward and to continuing to learn, make mistakes, and figure out what comes next‚Ä¶</p><p><em><strong>+ Georg didn‚Äôt ask me to share any of this but I‚Äôm happy to shout him out. I think he‚Äôs on to something with this and it was cool to spend time with him and see the aliveness and creative energy within his family. <a href="https://claritysessions.carrd.co/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Here is a link to learn more</a>.</strong></em></p><h3>#2 From Indonesian Tourism School to Selling Steel to Podcast App CEO</h3><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2ae11c8f-5550-4b10-aaec-1a71878228c9_1562x818.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/qVDJSxIYL3tcdAtomn-nVeycaH9_76hMPJkEXw5Fd-E=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYyYWUxMWM4Zi01NTUwLTRiMTAtYWFlYy0xYTcxODc4MjI4YzlfMTU2Mng4MTgucG5n 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/pQIH6QK8-MqYtI2ikL9z8wpmS3Ln6SplQXuTVrK-tLU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMmFlMTFjOGYtNTU1MC00YjEwLWFhZWMtMWE3MTg3ODIyOGM5XzE1NjJ4ODE4LnBuZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0P-8I- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wtUMkslk9Ja_" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/-bN1ab5rpUyKyB1qRsql3_qdzEWR-hcRoltWb7LWt4k=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3J